<subsection xml:id="subsec-identifying-angles-and-sides-of-right-angled-triangles-in-different-situations">
    <title>Identifying Angles and Sides of Right Angled Triangles </title>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Draw a right-angled triangle and label its vertices as <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>, with the right angle positioned at <m>P</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the side that is next to angle <m>Q</m>, excluding the hypotenuse.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Point out the hypotenuse, the side that lies opposite the <m>90</m>° angle.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Now repeat the same steps, but this time use angle <m>R</m> as your reference.

                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}.</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    A right-angled triangle always has one angle equal to <m>90</m>°. The other two angles must be acute angles
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    The sides that include the right angle are perpendicular to each other and the third side is called the hypotenuse.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    If you are given an angle in a right-angled triangle, the side opposite to that angle is called the opposite side, while the side next to the angle (excluding the hypotenuse) is called the adjacent side as shown below.
                </p>

                <image width="50%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <latex-image label="trianglePQRi">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    
                        % Triangle vertices
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (R) at (0,3);

                        % Fill the triangle with cyan color
                        \fill[cyan!30] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the triangle outline
                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                        % Right angle symbol at P
                        \draw (0.4,0) -- (0.4,0.4) -- (0,0.4);

                        % Label the vertices
                        \node[below left] at (P) {P};
                        \node[below right] at (Q) {Q};
                        \node[above left] at (R) {R};

                        % Label angle α at R
                        \node at (0.2,2.6) {$\alpha$};

                        % Label sides
                        \node[below] at (2,0) {Opposite};
                        \node[left] at (0,1.5) {Adjacent};
                        \node[above right, rotate=45] at (2.2,1.5) {Hypotenuse};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The figure below shows a right-angled triangle <m>PQR</m>. Name the sides which are opposite and adjucent to the angle <m>\theta</m> and identity the hypotenuse side.
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="trianglePQR">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                          % Triangle vertices
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (R) at (0,3);

                        % Fill the triangle with blue color
                        \fill[blue!20] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the triangle outline
                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                        % Right angle symbol at P
                        \draw (0.4,0) -- (0.4,0.4) -- (0,0.4);

                        % Label the vertices
                        \node[below left] at (P) {P};
                        \node[below right] at (Q) {Q};
                        \node[above left] at (R) {R};

                        % Draw a small arc to indicate angle θ at C

                        \node at (0.2,2.6) {$\theta$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>
                Side <m>PR</m> is adjacent to angle <m>\theta</m>. 
            </p>

            <p>
                Side <m>PQ</m> is opposite to angle <m>\theta</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                The hypotenuse is <m>QR</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>